evaluation.response:
Many people replay memories from years ago and wish they could take things back, but the truth is that this is a skill you can develop through practice. Here are some strategies to stop ruminating:
*   Engage in an activity: This could be something as simple as taking a few deep breaths, going for a walk, doing a few jumping jacks, or calling a friend. Most people find certain activities help them feel better when they are reminded of their traumatic experiences.
*   Write it out. Sometimes it helps to write thoughts or memories down. You can even write them down and then burn them. Reread them to see if there is a particular phrase or sentence that brings you right back to the memory you are trying to release.
*   Reframe negative thoughts. Oftentimes, it is helpful to acknowledge the negative thought and then provide some sort of validation or explanation to help you more easily dismiss it.&#x20;

The best way to stop ruminating is to develop a routine, uncomfortable as it may feel while you rewire your system. Make time for regular mental help sessions as it gets easier with practice and professional help.&#x20;

It can be really challenging to control the thoughts that come into my head, especially at night and when I'm feeling stressed.

Setting aside something to read in bed before going to sleep can help. If I wake up, it will be there to help me take my mind off things. Key is to choose a book that’s engaging enough to hold my attention, but not to a degree that will make me feel wired or overly stimulated. Reading can be a great way to calm my brain at night.

Additionally, I can try to challenge my negative thoughts by reframing them in a more realistic or positive way. For example, instead of thinking "I'm a horrible person for pushing people away," I can tell myself "I was struggling with my own stuff and didn't have the emotional resources to deal with other people's needs at the time. That doesn't mean I'm a bad person." These types of thoughts aren't always true, or could be an overestimation of a situation.&#x20;
